  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and regulations aimed at preventing money laundering:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) sets global standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\n2. The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime provides guidelines for member states to combat money laundering.\n\n3. The Basel Committee on Banking Supervision establishes principles for banks to prevent money laundering.\n\n4. Most countries have their own national anti-money laundering (AML) laws that require financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n\n5. International agreements like the Palermo Convention and the Merida Convention provide frameworks for cross-border cooperation in preventing financial crimes.\n\nThese laws typically require financial institutions to:\n- Conduct customer due diligence\n- Monitor and report suspicious activities\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement internal compliance programs\n\nPenalties for money laundering can include significant fines and criminal prosecution.",
